    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3275501955" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3275501955" />
    <a title="Scriptor Ignotus" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7422525-scriptor-ignotus"><img alt="Scriptor Ignotus" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1627441675p2/7422525.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3275501955?book_show_action=true">Apr 21, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Scriptor Ignotus" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Scriptor Ignotus" href="/user/show/7422525-scriptor-ignotus">Scriptor Ignotus</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780199540549" href="/book/show/3111577-the-consolation-of-philosophy">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7422525-scriptor-ignotus?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7422525-scriptor-ignotus?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3275501955" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14451951677892503113"><b>The Last Roman</b><br/><br/>Historians tell us that the Western Roman Empire ended in the year 476, when the boy-emperor Romulus Augustulus was compelled to surrender his diadem to a rebellious German warlord named Odoacer, but the heirs of Rome’s ancient senatorial aristocracy don’t seem to have noticed. With an aloofness that strikes the eye of retrospection as buffoonery, the Senate continued to meet in Rome, as if the new Italian kingdom was ruled from the <i>urbe aeterna</i> instead of Ravenna; continued to deb</span>
  <span id="freeText14451951677892503113" style="display:none"><b>The Last Roman</b><br><br>Historians tell us that the Western Roman Empire ended in the year 476, when the boy-emperor Romulus Augustulus was compelled to surrender his diadem to a rebellious German warlord named Odoacer, but the heirs of Rome’s ancient senatorial aristocracy don’t seem to have noticed. With an aloofness that strikes the eye of retrospection as buffoonery, the Senate continued to meet in Rome, as if the new Italian kingdom was ruled from the <i>urbe aeterna</i> instead of Ravenna; continued to debate the passions of statecraft with resounding, gesticulational philippics, as if anyone were still listening; continued to sniff the rarefied Palatine air with upturned patrician noses; and continued to appoint Consuls and Praetorian Prefects as if these once-prestigious officers, along with the Senate itself, were not subject to the arbitrary mercies of a succession of vulpinous laureled brigands: first Odoacer, and then the Ostrogothic king Theoderic, who routed and supplanted his predecessor with the tacit licensure of Constantinople in 493. <br><br>At the dawn of the sixth century, the leading light of this frivolous institution was Anicius Manlius Severinus Boethius. Born into one prominent family and adopted into another, Boethius had the honor not only of ascending to the Consulship himself, but also of seeing both of his sons attain to the office before he was selected as Theoderic’s <i>Magister Officiorum</i>: a position of far more tangible political influence roughly equivalent to that of a Chief of Staff in an American presidential administration. The appointment gave Boethius access to the inner corridors of power, but it also made him vulnerable to the tempers of a ruthless marauder with precarious claims to legitimacy and an increasingly paranoid disposition in light of his estrangement, as an Arian and a gently-Romanized Goth, from the politico-ecclesiastical Nicene Christian power center of Rome; which Theoderic long suspected, likely with justification, of a clandestine willingness to align itself with the eastern Emperor in support of an orthodox Christian imperial claimant who could depose him just as he had dispensed with Odoacer. <br><br>Matters came to a head in 523, when a senator named Albinus was accused by one of Theoderic’s confidants of denouncing the king in a secret missive sent to Constantinople. As Boethius was one of Albinus’s senatorial allies, he attempted to assure Theoderic of the falsity of the charge with one of the most poorly-worded statements in the history of the world. “If Albinus so acted,” Boethius proclaimed with the surety of one about to be strangled by his own words, “then I and the whole senate acted with one mind. It is false, my lord king.” <br><br>Intended to set the king at ease, the remark inflamed Theoderic’s conviction that the entire Senate was conspiring against him, and that Boethius was working to dull the scent of a senatorial coup from within the Ravenna court. Albinus was summarily put to death, and Boethius spent a year in imprisonment before his execution sometime between 524 and 526. The last light of a darkening age—the last Roman—was strangled with a cord and beaten to death with a club; a punishment common to recalcitrant slaves.*<br><br><b>Consolation</b><br><br><i>The Consolation of Philosophy</i> is exactly that: a learned and celebrated man is cast down from the heights of fortune, and his task is to call upon the eternal truths of philosophy, that divine and immutable wisdom that trembles not at death or despair, to reconcile his addled mind with the brute fact of his imminent obliteration. Fortune’s wheel, having raised him to the summit of prosperity, has thrown him to the ground with a lethal and terrifying velocity. The vicissitudes of fate have stripped him of all his worldly attainments—so what now remains? <br><br>As Boethius languishes in his despair, Philosophy appears to him as a beautiful woman with tattered garments: originally whole as the undefiled wisdom of Socrates, pieces have been torn away by greedy Stoics and Epicureans who imagine that the shreds they’ve taken represent the whole to which they rightfully belong. She is Sophia from the Biblical wisdom literature, Diotima from Plato’s <i>Symposium</i>, and a certain prefiguration of Dante’s Beatrice. She is truth as an inviting feminine companion; and discerning that Boethius has been blinded by his anguish to the benevolent order of creation and the true purpose of his life within it, she determines to lead him home from his spiritual exile. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1587454464i/29329591._SX540_.jpg" width="400" height="293" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Boethius’s error was to forget the eternal good for which all temporal goods are sought and within which all are contained. Like most of mankind, he mistook the vehicles through which men pursue the good—wealth, office, fame, pleasure—as the good itself, and by so doing he invested his mortal hopes in externalities that must always be captive to fortune. Any supposed good which is subject to the mutability of chance cannot be the good as such, because the good, by its nature, must lack nothing outside of itself. The good is the ontological original that is sufficient in itself: it is identical with God and experienced by human beings as happiness. To be happy, then—not sated, amused, or titillated—is to be divine. The cultivation of happiness, which one achieves through an introspective meditation on those vital elements of the self and the cosmic order that are impervious to the gyrations of happenstance, is thus a process of divinization through which the happy person <i>becomes God</i>; a process similar to the Orthodox Christian concept of <i>theosis</i>, but without the Palamite distinction between the divine essence and energies. <br><br>Boethius laments that there appears to be no divine order in the realm of justice; that the wicked flourish while the virtuous suffer. This notion too is dispelled by the purifying light of Philosophy. Since all rational natures seek the good, but only the virtuous obtain it, it must be concluded that only the virtuous possess power and potency, while the wicked, whatever their apparent circumstances in temporality, are distinctive in their impotence, fecklessness, perpetual discontent, and ultimately in their inhumanity. Since the wicked by nature seek the good but by necessity do not possess it, they must either be ignorant of the true good, lack the discipline and self-control to achieve it, or willfully and knowingly pursue evil, which sets them in rebellion against a natural order that undergirds the eternal part of themselves. Thus, according to Philosophy, those who are truly evil simply fall out of existence, and a “wicked person” is a contradiction in terms: wicked persons do not exist <i>as persons</i>, because in wickedness one descends to the subrational order of base animals. <br><br>Though the limitations of our perspective make it impossible for us to perfectly understand how God’s justice works itself out in the contingencies of events, Philosophy insists that there is really no such thing as bad fortune, because all things happen in accordance with God’s benevolent governance of the world. To demonstrate this, she distinguishes between providence and fate. Providence is the changeless, eternal “blueprint” of the world’s divine order, while fate is the outworking of providence in the flow of temporal causality. The weave of fate looks discordant to us, but only because we have an imperfect understanding of the providential underpinning of events. <br><br>But, Boethius asks, if God governs the world and directs everything towards the good, which is Himself, then can we truly say that human beings have free will? If God has foreknowledge of all events, both necessary and apparently indeterminate, would it not follow that either all events are predetermined, or that the ends of the willful actions of human beings are not known with certainty by God?<br><br>In her response, Philosophy articulates a theory that the mode of comprehension of a given truth is to some extent relative to the nature and capacities of the knower. The <i>thing</i> known does not of itself differ between knowers, but the <i>way</i> a thing is known differs according to the comprehension of the knower. Philosophy identifies four levels of cognition: sensation, imagination, reason, and understanding, each of which corresponds to ascending rungs in a ladder of intellectual ascent: inanimate objects, lesser animals, human beings, and God. Reason is exclusive to humanity, while understanding, which is exclusive to God, is the cognitive level at which free will and divine foreknowledge are reconciled. <br><br>Philosophy has established that God’s perspective is eternal, but she takes care to clarify the nature of eternality. It is not simply that God precedes the created order on a temporal level, but that He “grasps and possesses simultaneously the entire fulness of life without end; no part of the future is lacking to [Him], and no part of the past has escaped [Him]. [He] must always appear to [Himself] as in the present, and as governing [Himself]; the unending course of fleeting time [He] must possess as the here and now.” <br><br>From the divine perspective, which encompasses all others, all events, both past and future, are comprehended as if they were <i>present</i>; and what is present is always necessary. Future events, whether necessary or indeterminate from the human perspective, are known with as much certainty by God as those things which we observe to be true <i>at the present moment</i> are known to us. But there is nothing limiting for human beings in this divine, presentist certainty. Just because indeterminate outcomes are known by God as necessary does not mean that future events are not free in themselves. It is helpful to illustrate the meaning of necessity in this sense by pointing out that just because I am <i>necessarily</i> sitting at a computer at this present moment does not mean that I am not free to stand up and walk around. Thus, contrary to our intuition, events that have no certain outcome are witnessed by God with “an unerring and precise foreknowledge”. <br><br>And thus is the capstone of Philosophy’s consolation of our hapless Boethius:<br><br>“<i>The hopes which we rest in God, and the prayers addressed to him, are not in vain; when they are righteous, they cannot be ineffectual. So avoid vices, cultivate the virtues, raise your minds to righteous hopes, pour out your humble prayers to heaven. As long as you refuse to play the hypocrite, a great necessity to behave honourably is imposed on you, for your deeds are observed by the judge who sees all things</i>”<br><br>We can only wonder whether he remained true to his Lady’s wisdom in his final moments.<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br>*<i>Boethius's wife, Rusticiana, did well by her late husband when she reputedly tore down statues of Theoderic in advance of Belisarius's invasion of Italy.</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="14451951677892503113" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


